{"title_page": "Dutch Civilisation in the Seventeenth Century", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Dutch civilisation in the seventeenth century''''' (Dutch: ''Nederland's beschaving in de zeventiende eeuw'') is a book published in Dutch by the Dutch historian [[Johan Huizinga]] in 1941. It was first translated into English by [[Arnold Pomerans]] in 1968 and published by the [[Frederick Ungar Publishing Company]]. It was edited by [[Peter Geyl]] and [[F. W. N. Hugenholtz]].\n\n==Content==\nHuizinga's work analyses the causes, content and consequences of the seventeenth century in the Netherlands, a period that can be broadly subsumed under the title and concept of the [[Dutch Golden Age]]. In his view, the efflorescence of art, literature and economic activity that characterised that period was driven by certain key factors: the idea that Dutch society was differentiated from other countries in Europe, for instance, by being fundamentally middle-class. The involvement of the middle-class in public life led to a 'discussion culture' which helped foment new ideas and inventions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Roitman|first1=Jessica V.|title=The Same But Different?: Inter-cultural Trade and the Sephardim, 1595-1640|date=2011|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004202765|page=59|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OOLWe21CrTcC&pg=PA59 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> Religion was also an important factor here, according to Huizinga, particularly given the virtues of [[Calvinism]] (such as \"simplicity, thrift and cleanliness') and the two factors were related, for Calvinism had an inherently anti-aristocratic element to it which helped ensure its success amongst people from relatively modest and bourgeois backgrounds.<ref>{{cite book|last1=C. Scott Dixon, Dagmar Freist, Mark Greengrass (eds)|title=Living with Religious Diversity in Early-modern Europe|date=2009|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=0754666689|pages=28\u20139|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l9fVJYNd61oC&pg=PA29&dq=%22Dutch+civilisation+in+the+seventeenth+century,+and+other+essays%22+Huizinga&hl=en&sa=X&ei=deq-U577EMaEO7q2gKAB&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Dutch%20civilisation%20in%20the%20seventeenth%20century%2C%20and%20other%20essays%22%20Huizinga&f=false|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs with the rest of his oeuvre, Huizinga is concerned with a synthesis of historical analysis that incorporates art and culture as well as political, economic and social factors. He focuses upon a number of key artistic and cultural figures and developments in the Netherlands of the 17th century, including [[Frans Hals]], [[Rembrandt]], [[Hercules Seghers]] and [[Joost van den Vondel]] (as well as scientists such as [[Christiaan Huygens]]).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Huizinga|first1=Johan|title=Dutch civilisation in the seventeenth century, and other essays|year=1968|via=[[Internet Archive]]|publisher=Collins|url=https://archive.org/details/dutchcivilisatio0000huiz|url-access=registration|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n[[Category:1941 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:History books about the Dutch Golden Age]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Dutch civilisation in the seventeenth century''''' (Dutch: ''Nederland's beschaving in de zeventiende eeuw'') is a book published in Dutch by the Dutch historian [[Johan Huizinga]] in 1941. It was first translated into English by [[Arnold Pomerans]] in 1968 and published by the [[Frederick Ungar Publishing Company]]. It was edited by [[Peter Geyl]] and [[F. W. N. Hugenholtz]].\n\n==Content==\nHuizinga's work analyses the causes, content and consequences of the seventeenth century in the Netherlands, a period that can be broadly subsumed under the title and concept of the [[Dutch Golden Age]]. In his view, the efflorescence of art, literature and economic activity that characterised that period was driven by certain key factors: the idea that Dutch society was differentiated from other countries in Europe, for instance, by being fundamentally middle-class. The involvement of the middle-class in public life led to a 'discussion culture' which helped foment new ideas and inventions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Roitman|first1=Jessica V.|title=The Same But Different?: Inter-cultural Trade and the Sephardim, 1595-1640|date=2011|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004202765|page=59|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OOLWe21CrTcC&pg=PA59 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> Religion was also an important factor here, according to Huizinga, particularly given the virtues of [[Calvinism]] (such as \"simplicity, thrift and cleanliness') and the two factors were related, for Calvinism had an inherently anti-aristocratic element to it which helped ensure its success amongst people from relatively modest and bourgeois backgrounds.<ref>{{cite book|last1=C. Scott Dixon, Dagmar Freist, Mark Greengrass (eds)|title=Living with Religious Diversity in Early-modern Europe|date=2009|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=0754666689|pages=28\u20139|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l9fVJYNd61oC&pg=PA29&dq=%22Dutch+civilisation+in+the+seventeenth+century,+and+other+essays%22+Huizinga&hl=en&sa=X&ei=deq-U577EMaEO7q2gKAB&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Dutch%20civilisation%20in%20the%20seventeenth%20century%2C%20and%20other%20essays%22%20Huizinga&f=false|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs with the rest of his oeuvre, Huizinga is concerned with a synthesis of historical analysis that incorporates art and culture as well as political, economic and social factors. He focuses upon a number of key artistic and cultural figures and developments in the Netherlands of the 17th century, including [[Frans Hals]], [[Rembrandt]], [[Hercules Seghers]] and [[Joost van den Vondel]] (as well as scientists such as [[Christiaan Huygens]]).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Huizinga|first1=Johan|title=Dutch civilisation in the seventeenth century, and other essays|year=1968|via=[[Internet Archive]]|publisher=Collins|url=https://archive.org/details/dutchcivilisatio0000huiz|url-access=registration|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n[[Category:1941 books]]\n[[Category:History books about the Dutch Golden Age]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1941 bookstoCategory:1941 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dutch_Civilisation_in_the_Seventeenth_Century"}
